          "text": [
            "Visualizing and Predic0ng trend in global Life Expectancy from 2001 to 2019  1st Adebayo 2nd Azubuike 3rd Maddox-McGhee Schools of Applied Computa3onal Sci Schools of Applied Computa3onal Sci Schools of Applied Computa3onal Sci  Meharry Medical College Meharry Medical College Meharry Medical College  Nashville, USA Nashville, USA Nashville, USA  isaac.adebayo@mmc.edu charnisha.azubuike@mmc.edu michella.maddoxmcghee@mmc.edu Abstract—What factors drive longevity. Why are some island na6ons living longer than some developed na6ons. Longevity and life expectancy is a core issue that touches on the fundamental of livelihood, it drives immigra6on and emigra6on for a search of be=er quality of life, longevity contributes to brain drain of a region in search for a be=er opportunity to maximize the quality of a individual or family life. This project aims to explore this issue thoroughly by analzying the data from world bank via kaggle. The goal is to visualize which factors inﬂuences or drive longevity, predict the longevity of each dataset using machine learning and compare it to the actual value reported and suggest recommenda6ons for future work based on the data interpola6on. Index Terms—Life Expectancy, Public Health, Quality of Life \n",
            "I. INTRODUCTION Our project will analyze the trend and increase in life expectancy across the world during the pre-Covid era ranging from 2001- 2019. Factors to be examined are socioeconomic factors such as country investments in healthcare per GDP, educaNon spending per GDP , environmental management, region and various health metrics such as sanitaNon and diseases The overall goal of the project is to explore public health and the role of divergent factors on life expectancy. The intended audience includes everyone from policy makers who make policy on budget allocaNon, students (the role of educaNon in life expectancy) and the public who vote for legislators that enacts and oversees this body. Our hope is to guide our intended audience on the role and interconnecNon of each factors and highlight the most important factor or metrics that should be prioriNze for improvement per region to maximize life expectancy. II. DATASET AND FEATURES A. Data Descrip3on The structured dataset consists of categorical and numerical variable. The columns are straNﬁed into: ”Country Name”, ”Country Code”, ”Region”, ”Income Group”, ”Year”, ”Life Expectancy World Bank”, ”Prevalence of Undernourishment”, ”CO2”, ”Health Expenditure” %, ”EducaNon Expenditure”, ”Unemployment”, ”CorrupNon”, ”SanitaNon”, ”Injuries”, ”Communicable” and ”Non-communicable”. \n",
            "B. Data Informa3on The name of the dataset is life expectancy and socioeconomic (world bank) • Source: Kaggle • Link:h^ps://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mjshri23/lifeexpectancy-and-socio-economic-worldbank?utm source=chatgpt.com C. Data Size • No of rows are 3307 • No of columns are 16 • range: 2001 – 2019 • Country Name: Unique variable is 174 • Country Code: Unique variable is 174 • Region: Unique variable is 7 • Income Group: Unique variable is 7 • Year: Missing 0, Mismatched 0 • Life Expectancy World Bank: Missing 188 variable • Prevalence of Undernourishment: Missing 684 • CO2: Missing 152 • Health Expenditure %: Missing 180 • EducaNon Expenditure: Missing 1090 • Unemployment: Missing 304 • CorrupNon: Missing 2331 • SanitaNon: Missing 1247 D. Data Ini3al Observa3on Before performing any imputaNon to ﬁll missing values. Some columns such as (corrupNon) were found to consist of a high amount of missing values and were excluded from analysis. A quick overview of the dataset saw an increase in life expectancy as the year progress. Also observed were the exclusion of some countries in the dataset which will slightly alter the global results. E. Data Imputa3on Missing values were ﬁlled based on the mean or median per region reﬂecNng geographic similariNes among nearest neighboring countries. The column corrupNon was dropped due to a signiﬁcant high amount of missing values.\n",
            "\n",
